<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091690-0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 276964 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 16, 1990, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1037 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEEPING AN EYE OUT ON THE FOREST; 
</P>
<P>
REGION'S FIRE LOOKOUTS SEE END OF AN ERA ON THE HORIZON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE PADILLA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tom Fusek is one of a dying breed. 
</P>
<P>
From his perch 8,013 feet above sea level -- a tower near the border between 
Kern and Ventura counties -- Fusek keeps watch over the rugged ridges of Los 
Padres National Forest, scanning the horizon every few minutes, ready to radio 
firefighters at the first puffs of smoke. 
</P>
<P>
On a clear day, Fusek's 360-degree view includes the Sierra Nevada foothills, 
Bakersfield, Palmdale, the skyscrapers of downtown Los Angeles and even Santa 
Catalina Island. He said he once saw ships rounding San Pedro -- more than 85 
miles away. 
</P>
<P>
But this summer could be Fusek's last season as a professional fire lookout. 
</P>
<P>
Although still widely used in remote parts of Northern California, the lookouts 
have become an endangered species in the state and national forests of Southern 
California, phased out by budget cuts, technology, urban sprawl and smog. 
</P>
<P>
"They're getting few and far between," Don Trammell, district recreation 
officer at Los Padres, said. 
</P>
<P>
Once the backbone of the U.S. Forest Service's firefighting network from Kern 
to the Mexican border, lookout towers have been on the decline for more than 20 
years. The last towers in Angeles National Forest, which covers more than 
600,000 acres of Los Angeles County, were closed about eight years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Lookouts watch over the four counties encompassed by Los Padres from only three 
of the area's seven remaining towers -- Fusek's 54-year-old wooden tower at 
Frazier Mountain and two others near Big Sur. 
</P>
<P>
The Cleveland National Forest in San Diego County still operates two of its 
seven towers and the San Bernardino National Forest keeps three towers open 
using volunteers. A fourth tower in San Bernardino was reopened a few weeks ago 
-- with a paid lookout -- to stand guard over the forest during the hot, dry 
days of September. 
</P>
<P>
Of 65 lookout towers operated by the California Department of Forestry and Fire 
Protection, none are in the 11 southernmost counties. 
</P>
<P>
"The wild lands are getting crowded," Karen Terrill, a department spokeswoman, 
said. "And when you've got a subdivision next door, there's really no need for 
a lookout." 
</P>
<P>
Many fires are spotted by commercial and private pilots, forest officials said. 
In recent years, motorists have begun reporting fires by car phone. 
</P>
<P>
It costs up to $10,000 each year to operate the Frazier Mountain tower, and 
forest officials said financial considerations may force them to close the 
lookout after this fire season. 
</P>
<P>
Fusek admitted that, on some occasions, he has sounded alarms only to be told 
some camper or pilot reported the flames first. Even so, the Frazier Mountain 
tower and its commanding view can still mean the difference between a small 
fire and devastating blaze, Jim Smith, a fire management officer in Los Padres, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
For Fusek, the tower is a serene retreat from city life. Fusek, a tall and 
lanky native of North Hollywood who grew sick of traffic, smog and urban 
blight, turned his back on the city after graduating from Cal State Los Angeles 
with a bachelor's degree in geography in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
He worked as a welder, a laborer and a fire lookout in Sequoia National Forest 
before coming to Frazier Mountain in 1985. He lives in the tower's 
8-foot-by-8-foot room five days a week, on watch from 9:30 a.m. to 6 p.m., 
before returning for two days of rest at his house in Santa Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm at peace with the world when coming down after five days," he said. "I 
feel more lonely in the big city. There's a difference between loneliness and 
solitude." 
</P>
<P>
But solitude is not for everyone. 
</P>
<P>
Smith said forest personnel still chuckle about a lookout who, perhaps unable 
to handle the boredom of duty, got drunk many years ago and randomly fired a 
gun all over Frazier Mountain. The lookout radioed his superiors to report that 
someone was shooting at him. 
</P>
<P>
At Frazier Mountain, the solitude is broken occasionally by a stray hunter or 
hiker. The hunters, Fusek said wearily, always ask the same questions: Have you 
seen any deer? Where are the deer? Have you seen any bucks? 
</P>
<P>
Yes, he tells them. And that's part of the mountain's appeal. There are deer, 
coyotes, birds and, always, that inspiring view. 
</P>
<P>
The site, about seven miles west of Gorman, has been a fire lookout since 1905. 
The tower, a boxy wooden structure with peeling Army green paint, was built in 
1936 at Camuesa Peak in Santa Barbara County and then relocated after a forest 
fire destroyed the Frazier Mountain tower in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
It's equipped with a small bunk, a television set, a stove, and a contraption 
called the Osborne fire finder, which Fusek uses to plot the exact coordinates 
of a fire. Taped to the side of the fire finder is a Far Side cartoon of a 
lookout, burned to a crisp, surrounded by untouched forest. 
</P>
<P>
Tucked behind the bunk is a small insulated stool Fusek stands on during 
electrical storms for protection. The closest lightning strike he ever saw hit 
a nearby electrical transformer. 
</P>
<P>
Fusek is supposed to scan the mountains every 15 minutes. But in reality he is 
always on guard, and while chatting with visitors recently, he now and then 
shifted his eyes to the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
The worst blaze in Fusek's career at Frazier Mountain was the Fishbowls fire of 
1987, named for a campground several miles to the south. It was 11:50 a.m., 
Fusek said, when he casually glanced up and saw a blue-black plume. 
</P>
<P>
After reporting the fire, all Fusek could do was watch as 5,000 acres were 
charred. "It's kind of a helpless feeling for me," he said. 
</P>
<P>
There's more to being a lookout than just watching the horizon, he said. 
Lookouts must recognize the slight gradations of color and movement which 
distinguish a fire from dust devils or steam rising from a wet road warmed by 
the sun. 
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit, Smith reminded Fusek of smoke he reported seeing several 
days earlier. A helicopter flew over the site and the spotter decided it was 
only steam. 
</P>
<P>
But two days later, a fire broke out in the exact spot, Smith said. The blaze 
had been smoldering. Fusek had been right after all. He nodded slightly with 
satisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
Fusek admitted later that he has mixed feelings about reporting fires. "To 
prove yourself, you want to see a smoke," he said. "But you don't want to see a 
big smoke." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Fire lookouts such as Tom Fusek, shown above in his 54-year-old perch 
high above Los Padres National Forest, are becoming an endangered species in 
Southern California because of budget reductions and urban sprawl. Fusek can't 
afford to nap on the job. In the photo below, he is merely resting his eyes. He 
is on watch in the tower's small room five days a week from 9:30 a.m. to 6 p.m. 
; Photo, Tom Fusek's most important tool is the Osborne fire finder, which 
plots fire's coordinates. ; Photo, On a clear day, Tom Fusek can see 
skyscrapers in downtown Los Angeles. He's found peace and solitude on Frazier 
Mountain. JOEL P. LUGAVERE / Los Angeles Times; Photo, (Ventura County Edition) 
On a clear day, Tom Fusek can see the skyscrapers of downtown Los Angeles from 
his old lookout tower on Frazier Mountain. JOEL P. LUGAVERE / Los Angeles 
Times; Photo, (Ventura County Edition) Jim Smith, a fire management officer in 
Los Padres, checks in on Tom Fusek. A fire lookout's days are long and can 
often be lonely. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
