<HEADLINE>
<P>
DROSSIN RUNS DOWN ANOTHER RECORD TO LEAD AGOURA TO TITLE; 
</P>
<P>
CROSS-COUNTRY: CHARGERS EDGE PALOS VERDES IN WOODBRIDGE INVITATIONAL GIRLS' 
RACE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE GLAZE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Agoura High's Deena Drossin set a course record at the Woodbridge Invitational 
on Saturday in Irvine, her second record in two weeks, and the Charger girls' 
cross-country team ended a three-year drought against three-time defending 
state Division I champion Palos Verdes. 
</P>
<P>
Drossin, a senior, timed 17 minutes 4 seconds on the three-mile course at 
Woodbridge High, eclipsing the old mark of 17:05 set in 1987 by Melissa Sutton 
of Newbury Park. One week earlier, Drossin shattered Fillmore standout Nikki 
Shaw's record in the Seaside Invitational in Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
"The last half-mile I was relaxing until my coach told me I could get the 
record," said Drossin, who was named girls' athlete of the meet. "I was really 
pushing it the last 250 yards." 
</P>
<P>
Agoura Coach Bill Duley prefers Drossin avoid aiming for records. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not trying to go after the records," Duley said. "If they fall, they 
fall. This is not something we want to get caught up in from week to week." 
</P>
<P>
Behind Drossin's win and a sixth-place finish by Tiffany York (17:51), Agoura 
edged Palos Verdes, 61-62. Tustin (147) and Corona del Mar (162) placed third 
and fourth. 
</P>
<P>
"I know it counts more at the end of the season," Duley said. "But this is 
something we've been trying to do for three years." 
</P>
<P>
In 1987, '88 and '89, the Chargers finished second to Palos Verdes in the state 
Division I meet. Duley and Palos Verdes Coach Joe Kelly hope to continue their 
rivalry at the state level. 
</P>
<P>
Under the new alignment for the Southern Section and state championships, 
Agoura and Palos Verdes have been placed in Divisions II and III, respectively, 
based on smaller enrollment. But both schools petitioned the California 
Interscholastic Federation state office before Friday's deadline for placement 
in Division I, for schools with more than 2,021 students. 
</P>
<P>
The Agoura girls' team currently is ranked second in the nation and Palos 
Verdes is sixth, according to The Harrier magazine, a cross-country 
publication. "The good teams should compete with the big schools," Duley said. 
Agoura currently has 1,900 students and Palos Verdes 1,333. 
</P>
<P>
Westlake senior Jeannie Rothman timed 17:23 to finish second in the 
medium-schools race. 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Wilson of Newbury Park clocked 15:28 in winning the small-schools junior 
race and Agoura's Ryan Wilson won the medium-schools sophomore race in 15:36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091690-0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 277103 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 16, 1990, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 20; Column 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
412 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARINE'S SCORING TOSSES COMPLETE MOORPARK ROMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRENDAN HEALEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The only problem with Del Marine's debut as Moorpark College quarterback is 
that it does not leave Marine much room for improvement. 
</P>
<P>
Marine, who didn't enter the game against East Los Angeles College on Saturday 
night until the fourth quarter, could have played more, but how could he have 
played better? He threw only two passes, both for touchdowns -- including a 
54-yard strike to his brother Pete on his first pass as a Raider -- and 
finished with 77 yards passing. 
</P>
<P>
The two scoring passes provided the final touches to Moorpark's 38-3 
nonconference victory at East L.A. 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark led only 10-3 at halftime but scored four touchdowns in a little more 
than 10 minutes at the end of the third quarter and the beginning of the fourth 
to turn the game into a blowout. 
</P>
<P>
"We sputtered in the first half,' Moorpark Coach Jim Bittner said. 'We could 
have got stung. I was getting a little bit worried." 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark running backs Freddie Bradley and Jamal Anderson finished with 123 and 
90 yards, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
They didn't go through the East L.A. defense like a hot knife through butter -- 
more like a sledgehammer through butter. 
</P>
<P>
"I thought they both played very well," Bittner said. "I thought all our backs 
played well." 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark finished with 260 yards on the ground and 151 through the air. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley scored Moorpark's first touchdown of the second half when he shrugged 
off the East L.A. defensive line on a three-yard run. 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark scored late in the third quarter when John Corcoran picked off a 
Santiago Alvarez pass in the right flat, returned it inside the East L.A. 
20-yard line then tossed a lateral to James Jolicoeur, who ran for the 
touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
Marine's touchdown passes capped the scoring. Early in the fourth quarter, 
Marine hit Pete on an out-and-up with a tight spiral for a 54-yard touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
"The best thing about it was that I hit my brother," Marine said. 
</P>
<P>
On Moorpark's next series, he threw a 23-yard touchdown pass to Matt Young. 
</P>
<P>
Alvarez completed 23 of 46 passes for 154 yards but had a pass intercepted by 
Corcoran in the end zone in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark scored its first touchdown on its second possession of the game. 
</P>
<P>
Starting quarterback Kris Dutra rifled a high pass into the end zone, and wide 
receiver Curtis Marsh tipped it before cradling it for a 13-yard touchdown 
reception. 
</P>
<P>
Andrew Petroski added a 25-yard field goal on Moorpark's next possession, but 
Moorpark was held scoreless for the remainder of the half. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091690-0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 277104 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 16, 1990, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 20; Column 6 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
498 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLU LACKS FINISHING POWER, 22-6 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM COLEMAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the Cal Lutheran offense, that first touchdown of the season is kind of 
like the rabbit they use at dog races. It's out there in front of the Kingsmen, 
but they just can't seem to catch up to it. 
</P>
<P>
For the second consecutive weekend, the CLU offense failed to score a 
touchdown. And, not surprisingly, the Kingsmen lost another nonconference game 
Saturday, this time to UC Santa Barbara, 22-6, in Cal Lutheran's home opener. 
</P>
<P>
Unlike last week -- when CLU managed just two first downs and 87 yards in 
offense while being blown out by Azusa Pacific -- there was a silver lining to 
the Santa Barbara defeat. This time, Cal Lutheran was able to move the football 
up and down the field, just not into the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
The Kingsmen (0-2) rushed for 209 yards and had the football nine more minutes 
than UCSB, finishing with 319 yards to 318 for the Gauchos (1-1). 
</P>
<P>
"We made a tremendous amount of progress. I see definite glimmers of hope," Cal 
Lutheran Coach Joe Harper said. "We weren't defeated by UCSB today, we were 
defeated by CLU. 
</P>
<P>
"If the enemy is us, maybe we have a few things to do." 
</P>
<P>
Like work on the pass defense. Gaucho quarterback Mike Curtius completed 16 of 
30 passes for 250 yards and two second-quarter touchdowns, a 52-yard scoring 
strike to Johnny Ace and a 11-yard touchdown toss to Matt Perry. 
</P>
<P>
Curtius connected with Ace again on a 62-yard touchdown pass late in the second 
period, but Santa Barbara was flagged for illegal procedure, nullifying the 
score. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't see the flag and I ran down the field like a crazy man," Curtius 
said. "I felt like a fool." 
</P>
<P>
He couldn't have felt any worse than CLU punter Len Bradley, who watched a snap 
sail over his head in the second period and bounce out of the end zone for a 
safety, increasing UCSB's advantage to 8-3. The Gauchos had missed the 
point-after kick on their first touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
CLU freshman quarterback Feliciano Ramirez, who suffered through a 
three-for-17, two-interception performance against Azusa Pacific, played much 
better Saturday, completing 11 of 25 for 110 yards. Linebacker Dominic Freking 
intercepted Ramirez's first pass, however, returning it 40 yards to the CLU 11 
to set up Ross Bauer's ensuing two-yard touchdown run. 
</P>
<P>
"That was a big play," Santa Barbara Coach Rick Candaele said. "They were 
running the ball and running the ball, and the first time they throw it, we 
pick it (off)." 
</P>
<P>
Alex Papike accounted for all the CLU points, booting field goals of 27 and 41 
yards in the first and fourth quarters, respectively. The Kingsmen shunned 
field-goal attempts in favor of going for the end zone on two fourth-down plays 
inside the UCSB 10-yard line, but Ramirez threw incomplete on one occasion and 
was sacked on the other. 
</P>
<P>
"Without a doubt, we had something to prove today, we just didn't put the ball 
in the end zone," said CLU's Cassidy O'Sullivan, who led the team in rushing 
with 87 yards. "But we made great strides." 
</P>
<P>
Someday soon, those strides might even reach the end zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
